 orbit''\n|-\n| September 27 || bgcolor=LemonChiffon | Perihelion  #6 || {{cvt|20.35|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 129 || 112.5 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=6 | 2021\n| January 17 || bgcolor=LemonChiffon | Perihelion  #7 || {{cvt|20.35|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 129 || 112.5 ||\n|-\n| ''February 20'' || bgcolor=PowderBlue   | ''Venus flyby #4'' || ''2392 km'' || ''Outbound'' || ''Outside'' || ''Flybys 3 and 4 occur at the<br/> same point in Venus's orbit'' \n|-\n| April 29 || bgcolor=Cornsilk     | Perihelion  #8 || {{cvt|15.98|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 147 || 102 ||\n|-\n| August 9 || bgcolor=Cornsilk     | Perihelion  #9 || {{cvt|15.98|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 147 || 102 ||\n|-\n| ''October 16'' || bgcolor=PowderBlue   | ''Venus flyby #5'' || ''3786 km'' || ''Inbound'' || ''Inside'' || ''Flybys 5 and 6 occur at the<br/> same point in Venus's orbit''\n|-\n| November 21 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #10 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2022\n| February 25 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #11 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| June 1 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #12 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| September 6 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #13 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| December 11 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #14 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 2023\n| March 17 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #15 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| June 22 || bgcolor=PapayaWhip   | Perihelion #16 || {{cvt|13.28|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 163 || 96 ||\n|-\n| ''August 21'' || bgcolor=PowderBlue   | ''Venus flyby  #6'' || ''3939 km'' || ''Inbound'' || ''Inside'' || ''Flybys 5 and 6 occur at the<br/> same point in Venus's orbit'' \n|-\n| September 27 || bgcolor=Moccasin     | Perihelion #17 || {{cvt|11.42|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 176 || 92 ||\n|-\n| December 29 || bgcolor=Moccasin     | Perihelion #18 || {{cvt|11.42|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 176 || 92 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 2024\n| March 30 || bgcolor=Moccasin     | Perihelion #19 || {{cvt|11.42|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 176 || 92 ||\n|-\n| June 30 || bgcolor=Moccasin     | Perihelion #20 || {{cvt|11.42|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 176 || 92 ||\n|-\n| September 30 || bgcolor=Moccasin     | Perihelion #21 || {{cvt|11.42|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 176 || 92 ||\n|-\n| ''November 6'' || bgcolor=PowderBlue   | ''Venus flyby #7'' || ''317 km'' || ''Outbound'' || ''Outside'' ||\n|-\n| December 24 || bgcolor=Gold         | Perihelion #22 || {{cvt|9.86|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 192 || 88 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2025\n| March 22 || bgcolor=Gold         | Perihelion #23 || {{cvt|9.86|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 192 || 88 ||\n|-\n| June 19 || bgcolor=Gold         | Perihelion #24 || {{cvt|9.86|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 192 || 88 ||\n|-\n| September 15 || bgcolor=Gold         | Perihelion #25 || {{cvt|9.86|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 192 || 88 ||\n|-\n| December 12 || bgcolor=Gold         | Perihelion #26 || {{cvt|9.86|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 192 || 88 ||\n|}\n{{Note|distance|a|The perihelion distances above are from the center of the Sun.  For altitude above the surface, subtract one solar radius \u2248&nbsp;0.7&nbsp;Gm.}}\n\n{{Note|venus|b|Details on Venus flybys from Guo et al.<ref name=\"mission design\" />{{rp|6}}}} This was published in 2014, four years before the mission began. For a variety of reasons, including the fact that the launch had to be delayed at the last minute, actual details could differ from the ones presented in the work.\n\n{{Note|leg|c|'''Inbound''' indicates that the Venus flyby will take place after ''Parker''{{'}}s aphelion (in the case of the first flyby, after its launch), on its way to perihelion.  '''Outbound''' indicates that the Venus flyby will take place after ''Parker''{{'}}s perihelion, on its way to aphelion.}}\n\n{{Note|inside/outside|d|'''Inside''' indicates that the probe will pass in between Venus and the Sun. '''Outside''' indicates that the probe will pass beyond Venus from the Sun; the probe will briefly pass through Venus's shadow in those instances.}}\n\n{{Note|1storbit|e|The first orbital period of 174 days was the orbit established by the launch and course adjustments, and was the orbit the probe would have taken had nothing further happened to change it. That orbit was, per mission plan, never completed. On the probe's first inbound course towards the Sun, it made its first planned encounter with Venus, which shortened its orbit considerably.}}\n\n{{Note|VenAlt|f|The altitude is from the source cited,<ref name=\"mission design\"/>{{rp|6}} dated 2014. 2548 km comes to 1583 mi. NASA's <ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title= Parker Solar Probe Changed the Game Before it Even Launched|url= https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2018/parker-solar-probe-changed-the-game-before-it-even-launched|website=Parker Solar Probe News Center |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|date= October 4, 2018|access-date= December 26, 2018}}</ref> and Johns Hopkins's <ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= How A Change in Mission Design Unlocked the Journey to the Sun |url= http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=104 |website=Parker Solar Probe Mission News |publisher=NASA|date= October 4, 2018|access-date= December 26, 2018}}</ref> press releases (identical), say \"...came within about 1500 miles of Venus' surface ...\" A NASA blog <ref name=\"blogvenus\">{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title= Parker Solar Probe Successfully Completes First Venus Flyby|url= https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/10/03/parker-solar-probe-successfully-completes-first-venus-flyby/|website=NASA Blogs\u2014Parker Solar Probe |publisher=NASA|date= October 3, 2018|access-date= December 26, 2018}}</ref> says, \"...completed its flyby of Venus at a distance of about 1,500 miles ...\" Other news reports, presumably taking that information, also provide a figure of 2414 km. But neither the NASA/Hopkins press release nor the blog gives a figure in kilometers.<br/>\nBoth the NASA and Hopkins press releases say that the flyby reduced the speed of the ''Parker Solar Probe'' (relative to the Sun) by about 10%, or 7,000 mph. This altered the orbit, bringing perihelion about 4 million miles closer to the Sun than it would have been without the gravity assist.}}\n\n{{Note|compare|g|By way of comparison, the planet [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] orbits the Sun at a distance varying from about 46.0&nbsp;Gm (46,001,200&nbsp;km) at its closest to about 69.8&nbsp;Gm (69,816,900&nbsp;km) at its farthest.}}\n\n{{Note|obsextend|h|After the second solar encounter phase, ''Parker Solar Probe'' was able to download much more data than NASA had expected. So NASA announced a substantial extension of the third solar encounter phase from 11 days to about 35 days. The observational instruments were turned on when ''Parker Solar Probe'' came within 0.45 [[Astronomical unit|au]] on the inbound trip, and are planned to run until the probe reaches about 0.50 au outbound.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=126|title=Parker Solar Probe Gets Extra Observation Time|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=August 16, 2018|website=Parker Solar Probe News Center|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n== Operational history ==\n[[File:Parker Solar Probe Flyby of Venus.svg|thumb|right|The second flyby of Venus on December 26, 2019. The velocity decreases by 2.9&nbsp;km/s to 26&nbsp;km/s (red circle), shifting the spacecraft to a new orbit closer to the Sun.]]\n* Launch occurred on August 12, 2018, at 3:31&nbsp;a.m. EDT, 07:31 UTC. The spacecraft operated nominally after launching. During its first week in space it deployed its high-gain antenna, magnetometer boom, and electric field antennas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2018/08/19/first-mission-milestones-accomplished-on-nasas-newly-launched-parker-solar-probe/|title=First milestones accomplished on NASA's newly-launched Parker Solar Probe \u2013 Spaceflight Now|website=spaceflightnow.com|language=en-US|access-date=August 22, 2018}}</ref> The spacecraft performed its first scheduled trajectory correction on August 20, 2018, while it was 5.5 million miles from Earth, and travelling at {{convert|63569|km/h|abbr=on}} <ref>[http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=96 After Near-Perfect Trajectory Maneuver, Parker Solar Probe On Course To Touch The Sun]. NASA. August 21, 2018.</ref>\n* Instrument activation and testing began in early September 2018. On September 9, the two [[WISPR]] telescopic cameras performed a successful [[first light (astronomy)|first-light]] test, transmitting wide-angle images of the background sky towards the [[galactic center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/09/19/illuminating-first-light-data-from-parker-solar-probe/|website=NASA Blogs: Parker Solar Probe|title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe|date=September 19, 2018|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* The probe successfully performed the first of the seven planned Venus flybys on October 3, 2018, where it came within about {{convert|1500|mi}} of Venus in order to reduce the probe's speed and orbit closer to the Sun <ref name=\"blogvenus\"/>\n* The first scientific observations were transmitted in December 2018 <ref>{{cite web |last1=Garner|first1=Rob|title=Preparing for Discovery With NASA's Parker Solar Probe |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2018/preparing-for-discovery-with-nasas-parker-solar-probe|website=nasa.gov|publisher=NASA|accessdate=March 9, 2019|date=December 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94|title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun|last=Brown|first=Geoffrey|date=August 12, 2018|work=Parker Solar Probe|access-date=August 13, 2018|last2=Brown|first2=Dwayne|language=en|last3=Fox|first3=Karen}}</ref>\n* NASA announced that on January 19, 2019, the Parker Solar Probe reached its first aphelion, thus completing its first full orbit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2019/01// |website=NASA Blogs: Parker Solar Probe|title=All Systems Go As Parker Solar Probe Begins Second Sun Orbit|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=May 11, 2019}}</ref> According to the Horizons system,<ref>{{cite web |title=HORIZONS System |publisher=Jet Propulsion Laboratory, NASA|url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/?horizons}} [https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/horizons.cgi#results Data file]</ref> on January 20, 2019 at 01:12 UTC, the space ship reached a distance of 0.9381 au\n* On November 12, 2019, the data from the first two flybys of the Sun (October 31 \u2013 November 12, 2018, and March 30 \u2013 April 19, 2019) was released to the public <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/parker-solar-probe-first-sun-data-goes-public.html|title=The 1st Sun Details from NASA's Parker Solar Probe Are Out. And They're Hot!|last=Bartels|first=Meghan|website=Space.com |language=en|url-status=live|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Findings ==\nOn December 4, 2019, the first four research papers were published describing findings during the spacecraft's first two dives near the Sun.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verscharen|first=Daniel|date=December 4, 2019|title=A step closer to the Sun's secrets|journal=Nature|volume=576|issue=7786|pages=219\u2013220|language=en|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-03665-3|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/science/nasa-parker-solar-probe-pictures.html|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe Is Unlocking the Sun's Mysteries|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|date=December 4, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=McComas|first=D. J.|last2=Christian|first2=E. R.|last3=Cohen|first3=C. M. S.|last4=Cummings|first4=A. C.|last5=Davis|first5=A. J.|last6=Desai|first6=M. I.|last7=Giacalone|first7=J.|last8=Hill|first8=M. E.|last9=Joyce|first9=C. J.|last10=Krimigis|first10=S. M.|last11=Labrador|first11=A. W.|date=December 4, 2019|title=Probing the energetic particle environment near the Sun|journal=Nature|volume=576|issue=7786|language=en|pages=223\u2013227|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1811-1|issn=1476-4687}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Howard|first=R. A.|last2=Vourlidas|first2=A.|last3=Bothmer|first3=V.|last4=Colaninno|first4=R. C.|last5=DeForest|first5=C. E.|last6=Gallagher|first6=B.|last7=Hall|first7=J. R.|last8=Hess|first8=P.|last9=Higginson|first9=A. K.|last10=Korendyke|first10=C. M.|last11=Kouloumvakos|first11=A.|date=December 4, 2019|title=Near-Sun observations of an F-corona decrease and K-corona fine structure|journal=Nature|volume=576|issue=7786|language=en|pages=232\u2013236|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1807-x|issn=1476-4687}}</ref> They reported the direction and strength of the Sun's magnetic field, and described the unusually frequent and short-lived changes in the direction of the Sun's magnetic field.  These measurements confirm the hypothesis that [[Alfv\u00e9n wave]]s are the leading candidates for understanding the mechanisms that underlie the [[coronal heating problem]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bale|first=S. D.|last2=Badman|first2=S. T.|last3=Bonnell|first3=J. W.|last4=Bowen|first4=T. A.|last5=Burgess|first5=D.|last6=Case|first6=A. W.|last7=Cattell|first7=C. A.|last8=Chandran|first8=B. D. G.|last9=Chaston|first9=C. C.|last10=Chen|first10=C. H. K.|last11=Drake|first11=J. F.|date=December 4, 2019|title=Highly structured slow solar wind emerging from an equatorial coronal hole|journal=Nature|volume=576|issue=7786|language=en|pages=237\u2013242|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1818-7|issn=1476-4687}}</ref>  The probe observed approximately a thousand \"rogue\" magnetic waves in the solar atmosphere that instantly increase [[solar winds]] by as much as {{convert|300000|mph|kph}} and in some cases completely reverse the local [[magnetic field]].<ref name=:0/><ref name=:1/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Witze|first=Alexandra|date=December 4, 2019|title=Sun-bombing spacecraft uncovers secrets of the solar wind|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|language=en|volume=576|issue=7785|pages=15\u201316|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-03684-0|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Drake|first=Nadia|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2019/12/sun-keeps-getting-stranger-parker-solar-probe-shows/|title=The sun keeps getting stranger, dive-bombing solar probe shows|date=December 4, 2019|work=[[National Geographic]]|language=en|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> They also reported that, using the \"beam of electrons that stream along the magnetic field\", they were able to observe that \"the reversals in the Sun's magnetic field are often associated with localized enhancements in the radial component of the plasma velocity (the velocity in the direction away from the Sun's centre)\". The researchers found a \"surprisingly large [[azimuth]]al component of the plasma velocity (the velocity perpendicular to the radial direction). This component results from the force with which the Sun's rotation slingshots plasma out of the corona when the plasma is released from the coronal magnetic field\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kasper|first=J. C.|last2=Bale|first2=S. D.|last3=Belcher|first3=J. W.|last4=Berthomier|first4=M.|last5=Case|first5=A. W.|last6=Chandran|first6=B. D. G.|last7=Curtis|first7=D. W.|last8=Gallagher|first8=D.|last9=Gary|first9=S. P.|last10=Golub|first10=L.|last11=Halekas|first11=J. S.|date=December 4, 2019|title=Alfv\u00e9nic velocity spikes and rotational flows in the near-Sun solar wind|journal=Nature|volume=576|issue=7786|language=en|pages=228\u2013231|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1813-z|issn=1476-4687|hdl=10150/636481|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n\nParker discovered evidence of a [[cosmic dust]] free zone of 3.5 million miles (5.6 million kilometres) radius from the Sun, due to vaporisation of cosmic dust particles by the Sun's radiation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencealert.com/the-sun-s-magnetic-field-appears-to-unexpectedly-flip-and-scientists-don-t-know-what-s-going-on|title=Scientists 'Blown Away' by Unexpected Results From NASA's Sun-Kissing Solar Probe|last=Futurism|first=Victor Tangermann|website=ScienceAlert|language=en-gb|access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{annotated link|Living With a Star}}\n* {{annotated link|Advanced Composition Explorer}} (ACE), launched 1997\n* {{annotated link|List of vehicle speed records}}\n\n;Sun observation spacecraft\n* {{annotated link|Solar and Heliospheric Observatory}}, launched 1995\n* {{annotated link|Solar Dynamics Observatory}}, ''SDO'', launched 2010\n* {{annotated link|Helios (spacecraft)|''Helios''}}, a pair of spacecraft launched in the 1970s to approach the Sun inside the orbit of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], {{solar radius|63}}\n* {{annotated link|Solar Orbiter}} (launched in 2020), {{solar radius|60}}\n* {{annotated link|STEREO}}, launched 2006\n* {{annotated link|TRACE}}, launched 1998\n* {{annotated link|WIND (spacecraft)|''WIND''}}, launched 1994\n* {{annotated link|Ulysses (spacecraft)|''Ulysses''}}, solar polar orbiter (1990\u20132009)\n\n;Spacecraft design\n* {{annotated link|Spacecraft thermal control}}\n* ''[[MESSENGER]]'', Mercury orbiter (2011\u20132015) with sun shield\n* {{annotated link|Sunshield (JWST)}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/ ''Parker Probe Plus''] at [[Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory]] (JHUAPL)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110719221441/http://solarprobe.jhuapl.edu/mission/docs/SolarProbeME.pdf ''Solar Probe Plus''] (Mission Engineering Report; JHUAPL)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160828040133/http://science.nasa.gov/about-us/smd-programs/heliophysics-research/ Heliophysics Research] (NASA)\n* [http://ehpd.gsfc.nasa.gov/ Explorers and Heliophysics Projects Division] (EHPD; NASA)\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe ''Parker Solar Probe''] (data and news; NASA)\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/video/science/100000006012333/nasa-parker-solar-probe.html ''Parker Solar Probe''] (Video/3:45; [[NYT]]; August 12, 2018)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUClxcUbuNM ''Parker Solar Probe''] (Video\u2014360\u00b0/3:27; [[NASA]]; September 6, 2018)\n\n{{Psp}}\n{{Sun spacecraft}}\n{{Solar System probes}}\n{{2018 in space}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2018}}\n{{Extreme motion}}\n\n[[Category:Space probes launched in 2018]]\n[[Category:Artificial satellites orbiting the Sun]]\n[[Category:Missions to the Sun]]\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Delta IV rockets]]\n[[Category:Parker Solar Probe| ]]\n[[Category:Living With a Star Program]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|NASA robotic spacecraft to probe the outer corona of the Sun}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name              = Parker Solar Probe\n| names_list        = Solar Probe (before 2002)<br/>Solar Probe Plus (2010\u20132017)<br/>Parker Solar Probe (since 2017)\n| image             = Parker Solar Probe.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| image_caption     = An artistic rendition of the Parker Solar Probe.\n| image_alt         = Digital model of a spacecraft with a bus attached to a larger sun-shield. Two small solar panels are attached to the side of the bus, along with four rear-facing antennas.\n| mission_type      = [[Heliophysics]]\n| operator          = {{nowrap|[[NASA]] / [[Applied Physics Laboratory]]}}\n| COSPAR_ID         = 2018-065A\n| SATCAT            = 43592\n| website           = {{url| http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/|}}\n| mission_duration  = 7 years (nominal mission)<br/>Elapsed: {{time interval|August 12, 2018, 07:31|show=ymd}}\n| manufacturer      = [[Applied Physics Laboratory]]\n| launch_mass       = {{cvt|685|kg|lb}}<ref name='extreme'>[http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/index.php#spacecraft Parker Solar Probe \u2013 Extreme Engineering]. NASA.</ref>\n| dry_mass          = {{cvt|555|kg|lb}}\n| payload_mass      = {{cvt|50|kg|lb}}\n| dimensions        = {{cvt|1.0|x|3.0|x|2.3|m|ft}}\n| power             = 343 [[Watt|W]] (at closest approach)\n| launch_date       = August 12, 2018, 07:31 UTC{{r|NYT-20180812-kc|NYT-20180811}}<ref name=\"launch date\">{{cite web|url= https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/parker-solar-probe-ready-for-launch-on-mission-to-the-sun|title=Parker Solar Probe Ready for Launch on Mission to the Sun|publisher=[[NASA]] |access-date=August 10, 2018|date=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Delta IV Heavy]] / [[Star (rocket stage)|Star-48BV]]<ref name=\"Delta 4\">{{cite news|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/03/18/delta-4-heavy-selected-for-launch-of-solar-probe/|title=Delta 4-Heavy selected for launch of solar probe|date=March 18, 2015|accessdate=March 18, 2015|work=Spaceflight Now|last=Clark|first=Stephen}}</ref>\n| launch_site       = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 37|SLC-37]]\n| launch_contractor = [[United Launch Alliance]]\n| orbit_reference   = [[Heliocentric orbit|Heliocentric]]\n| orbit_inclination = 3.4\u00b0\n| orbit_period      = 88 days\n| orbit_semimajor   = {{convert|0.388|AU|AU+e6km+e6mi|abbr=unit|order=out}}\n| orbit_apoapsis    = {{convert|0.73|AU|AU+e6km+e6mi|abbr=unit|order=out}}{{r|feasible}}\n| orbit_periapsis   = {{convert|9.86|solar radius|AU+e6km+e6mi+solar radius|abbr=unit|order=out|sigfig=2}}{{refn|group=note|Mission planning used a perihelion of {{cvt|9.5|solar radius|Gm+e6mi|lk=in}}, or {{cvt|8.5|solar radius|Gm+e6mi}} altitude above the surface,{{r|feasible}} but later documents all say {{solar radius|9.86}}. The exact value will not be finalized until the seventh Venus gravity assist in 2024. Mission planners might decide to alter it slightly before then.}}\n| apsis             = helion\n| trans_band        = [[Ka band|K<sub>a</sub>-band]]<br/>[[X-band]]\n| interplanetary    = [[Sun]]\n| instruments_list  = {{Infobox spaceflight/Instruments\n  |acronym1 = SWEAP    |name1 = Solar Wind Electrons Alphas and Protons Investigation\n  |acronym2 = SPC      |name2 = Solar Probe Cup\n  |acronym3 = SPAN     |name3 = Solar Probe Analyzers\n  |acronym4 = WISPR    |name4 = Wide-field Imager for Solar Probe\n  |acronym5 = [[FIELDS]]   |name5 = Electromagnetic Fields Investigation\n  |acronym6 = IS\u2609IS\u2012EPI |name6 = Integrated Science Investigation of the Sun Energetic Particle Instruments<ref>{{cite web|title=Parker Solar Probe Science Gateway |url=https://sppgway.jhuapl.edu/ |website=sppgway.jhuapl.edu |accessdate=October 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n  }}\n| insignia          = Parker Solar Probe insignia.png\n| insignia_size     = 150x150px\n| insignia_alt      = Artwork of the spacecraft next to the Sun, enclosed in a circle with a yellow border. The words \"Parker Solar Probe\" are placed around the interior of the border, while the words \"a mission to touch the Sun\" are written inline in a smaller font in the bottom right of the image.\n| insignia_caption  = The official insignia for the Parker Solar Probe mission.\n}}\n\nThe '''Parker Solar Probe''' (abbreviated '''PSP'''; previously '''Solar Probe''', '''Solar Probe Plus''' or '''Solar Probe+''') <ref name=\"bbc22jl18\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/jul/22/parker-solar-probe-set-the-controls-for-the-edge-of-the-sun|title=Parker Solar Probe: set the controls for the edge of the sun...|work=The Guardian|first=Stuart|last=Clark|date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> is a [[NASA]] [[robotic spacecraft]] launched in 2018, with the mission of repeatedly probing and making observations of the outer [[solar corona|corona]] of the [[Sun]].<ref name=\"NYT-20180811\">{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=NASA Delays Parker Solar Probe Launch|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/science/parker-solar-probe-launch.html|date=August 11, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20170531\">{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=Newly Named NASA Spacecraft Will Aim Straight for the Sun|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/science/nasa-parker-solar-probe-sun.html|date=May 31, 2017|work=New York Times|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=feasible>{{cite paper|author=Applied Physics Laboratory|title=Feasible Mission Designs for Solar Probe Plus to Launch in 2015, 2016, 2017, or 2018|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |url=http://www.physics.umd.edu/courses/Phys410/Anlage_Spring13/2015-2018missions.pdf|date=November 19, 2008}}</ref> It will approach to within 9.86 [[solar radius|solar radii]] (6.9 million km or 4.3 million miles) <ref name=\"PressKit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/parkersolarprobe_presskit_august2018_final.pdf|title=NASA Press Kit: Parker Solar Probe|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=NASA|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp|title=Parker Solar Probe\u2014eoPortal Directory\u2014Satellite Missions|website=directory.eoportal.org|language=en-US|access-date=October 6, 2018}}</ref> from the center of the Sun and by 2025 will travel, at closest approach, as fast as {{convert|430000|mph|kph|abbr=on|order=flip}}, or 0.064% the speed of light.<ref name=\"PressKit\"/><ref name=\"NASA-20180809\">{{cite web|last=Garner|first=Rob|title=Parker Solar Probe: Humanity's First Visit to a Star|url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-humanity-s-first-visit-to-a-star|date=August 9, 2018|work=[[NASA]]|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe project was announced in the fiscal 2009 budget year. The cost of the project is US$1.5 billion. [[Johns Hopkins University]] [[Applied Physics Laboratory]] designed and built the spacecraft,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/science/bs-md-apl-nasa-solar-probe-20180812-story.html|title=NASA probe operated from Johns Hopkins lab in Laurel rockets toward sun for closest look yet |last=Bogel-Burroughs|first=Nicholas|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|access-date=August 16, 2018|last2=Dunn|first2=Marcia|language=en-US}}</ref> which was launched on August 12, 2018.<ref name=\"NYT-20180812-kc\">{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on NASA Voyage to 'Touch the Sun'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/11/science/parker-solar-probe-launch.html|date=August 12, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> It became the first NASA spacecraft named after a living person, honoring physicist [[Eugene Newman Parker]], professor emeritus at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=NASA|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/nasa-renames-solar-probe-mission-to-honor-pioneering-physicist-eugene-parker|title=NASA Renames Solar Probe Mission to Honor Pioneering Physicist Eugene Parker|date=May 31, 2017|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA [[memory card]] containing the names of over 1.1 million people was mounted on a plaque and installed below the spacecraft's high-gain antenna on May 18, 2018.<ref>\n{{cite news|title=NASA's Solar Parker Probe To Carry Over 1.1 Million Names To The Sun|url=https://headlinestoday.org/science/1402/nasas-solar-parker-probe-to-carry-over-1-1-million-names-to-the-sun/|access-date=August 10, 2018|agency=Headlines Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810235439/https://headlinestoday.org/science/1402/nasas-solar-parker-probe-to-carry-over-1-1-million-names-to-the-sun/|archive-date=August 10, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The card also contains photos of Parker and a copy of his 1958 scientific paper predicting important aspects of [[solar physics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp|title=NASA Press Kit: Parker Solar Probe|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=NASA|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 29, 2018, at about 18:04 UTC, the spacecraft became the closest ever artificial object to the Sun. The previous record, {{convert|26.55|e6mi|order=flip}} from the Sun's surface, was set by the ''[[Helios (spacecraft)|Helios 2]]'' spacecraft in April 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/science/nasas-parker-solar-probe-breaks-record-becomes-closest-spacecraft-to-the-sun|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe breaks record, becomes closest spacecraft to the Sun|first=James|last=Rogers|date=October 29, 2018|website=Fox News}}</ref> As of its January 29, 2020, [[perihelion]], the Parker Solar Probe's closest approach is {{convert|11.6|e6mi|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frazier|first1=Sarah|title=Parker Solar Probe Reports Successful Record-Setting Fourth Close Encounter of the Sun |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2020/02/01/parker-solar-probe-reports-successful-record-setting-fourth-close-encounter-of-the-sun/|publisher=NASA|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref> This will be surpassed after each successive [[Venus]] [[flyby (spaceflight)|flyby]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:KSC-20180605-PH GEB01 0116 (41073463690).jpg|thumb|left|upright|A light bar testing in the [[Astrotech Corporation|Astrotech]] processing facility.]]\n[[File:NASA's Parker Solar Probe Mission Launches to Touch the Sun.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:31|right|The launch of the probe.]]\n\nThe Parker Solar Probe concept originates in the 1958 report by the Fields and Particles Group (Committee 8 of the [[National Academy of Sciences]]' Space Science Board <ref>{{cite book|title=First Among Equals: The Selection of NASA Space Science Experiments|chapter=&sect;3.2.2: Physics of Fields and Particles in Space|first=John E.|last=Naugle|series=The NASA History Series|year=1991|page=34 |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19910018746.pdf#page=49|chapter-url=https://history.nasa.gov/SP-4215/ch3-2.html#3.2.2|lccn=91-13286|id=NASA SP-4215}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=National Academy of Sciences Establishes Space Science Board|date=August 3, 1958|first=Detlev W.|last=Bronk|authorlink=Detlev Bronk|publisher=National Academy of Sciences &ndash; National Research Council|url=https://sites.nationalacademies.org/cs/groups/ssbsite/documents/webpage/ssb_052237.pdf}}</ref>) which proposed several space missions including \"a solar probe to pass inside the orbit of Mercury to study the particles and fields in the vicinity of the Sun\".<ref name=McNutt>{{cite conference|title=Solar Probe Plus: A Scientific Investigation Sixty Years in the Making|first=Ralph L. Jr. |last=McNutt|date=December 15, 2015|conference=American Geophysical Union Fall Meeting|bibcode=2015AGUFMSH24A..01M|url=https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/webprogram/Paper61485.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A 60-year race to touch the Sun|first=Ian|last=Graber-Stiehl|date=August 13, 2018|journal=[[Astronomy (magazine)|Astronomy]]|url=http://astronomy.com/news/2018/08/60-year-race-to-the-sun}}</ref>  Studies in the 1970s and 80s reaffirmed its importance,{{r|McNutt}} but it was always postponed due to cost.<!-- Ref: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pG44eEjYmFg&t=1280 Justin Casper - First Discoveries by Parker Solar Probe and the SWEAP Investigation (CfA Colloquium, January 20, 2020)--> A cost-reduced ''Solar Orbiter'' mission was studied in the 1990s, and a more capable ''Solar Probe'' mission served as one of the centerpieces of the [[eponym]]ous Outer Planet/Solar Probe (OPSP) program formulated by [[NASA]] in the late 1990s. The first three missions of the program were planned to be: the ''Solar Orbiter'', the [[Pluto]] and [[Kuiper belt]] reconnaissance mission ''[[Pluto Kuiper Express]]'', and the ''[[Europa Orbiter]]'' astrobiology mission focused on [[Europa (moon)|Europa]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=McNamee Chosen to Head NASA's Outer Planets/Solar Probe Projects|url=http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=5174|publisher=Jet Propulsion Laboratory|access-date=January 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102204522/http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=5174|archive-date=January 2, 2017|date=April 15, 1998|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=opsp>{{cite conference |last1=Maddock |first1=Robert W.|last2=Clark|first2=Karla B.|last3=Henry|first3=Curt A.|last4=Hoffman|first4=Pamela J.|title=The Outer Planets/Solar Probe Project: \"Between an ocean, a rock, and a hot place\"\n|url=https://trs.jpl.nasa.gov/bitstream/handle/2014/20792/98-1875.pdf|conference=1999 IEEE Aerospace Conference|date=March 7, 1999|bibcode=1999aero....1..383M}}</ref>\n\nThe original ''Solar Probe'' design used a [[gravity assist]] from [[Jupiter]] to enter a polar orbit which dropped almost directly toward the Sun. While this explored the important solar poles and came even closer to the surface (3&nbsp;{{solar radius}}, a perihelion of 4&nbsp;{{solar radius}}),{{r|opsp}} the extreme variation in solar irradiance made for an expensive mission and required a [[radioisotope thermal generator]] for power. The trip to Jupiter also made for a long mission ({{frac|3|1|2}} years to first solar perihelion, 8 years to second).\n\nFollowing the appointment of [[Sean O'Keefe]] as [[List of Administrators and Deputy Administrators of NASA|Administrator of NASA]], the entirety of the OPSP program was canceled as part of President [[George W. Bush]]'s request for the [[2003 United States federal budget]].<ref name=\"space.com-1\">{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Brian|title=NASA Kills Europa Orbiter; Revamps Planetary Exploration |url=http://www.space.com/news/nasa_budget_020204.html|website=Space.com|publisher=[[Purch Group]]|access-date=January 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020210015816/http://www.space.com/news/nasa_budget_020204.html|archive-date=February 10, 2002|date=February 4, 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> Administrator O'Keefe cited a need for a restructuring of NASA and its projects, falling in line with the Bush Administration's wish for NASA to refocus on \"research and development, and addressing management shortcomings\".<ref name=\"space.com-1\"/>\n\nThe cancellation of the program also resulted in the initial cancellation of ''[[New Horizons]]'', the mission that eventually won the competition to replace ''Pluto Kuiper Express'' in the former OPSP program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Savage|first1=Donald|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/text/pluto_pr_20011129.txt|title=NASA Selects Pluto\u2013Kuiper Belt Mission Phase B Study|publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA)|date=November 29, 2001|access-date=July 9, 2015|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZsCefQyx?url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/text/pluto_pr_20011129.txt|archive-date=July 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> That mission, which would eventually be launched as the first mission of the [[New Frontiers program]], a conceptual successor to the OPSP program, would undergo a lengthy political battle to secure funding for its launch, which occurred in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hand|first1=Eric |title=Feature: How Alan Stern's tenacity, drive, and command got a NASA spacecraft to Pluto|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/people-events/2015/06/feature-how-alan-stern-s-tenacity-drive-and-command-got-nasa-spacecraft-pluto|website=Science (journal)|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|date=June 25, 2015|access-date=July 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626200636/http://news.sciencemag.org/people-events/2015/06/feature-how-alan-stern-s-tenacity-drive-and-command-got-nasa-spacecraft-pluto|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, plans for the ''Solar Probe'' mission were incorporated into a lower-cost ''Solar Probe Plus''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fazekas|first1=Andrew|title=New NASA Probe to Dive-bomb the Sun |url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/09/100909-science-space-sun-new-nasa-solar-probe-plus-dive-bomb/|website=National Geographic|publisher=21st Century Fox/National Geographic Society|access-date=January 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102202026/http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/09/100909-science-space-sun-new-nasa-solar-probe-plus-dive-bomb/|archive-date=January 2, 2017|url-status=live|date=September 10, 2010}}</ref> The redesigned mission uses multiple Venus gravity assists for a more direct flight path, which can be powered by [[Solar panels on spacecraft|solar panels]]. It also has a higher perihelion, reducing the demands on the thermal protection system.\n\nIn May 2017, the spacecraft was renamed ''Parker Solar Probe'' in honor of astrophysicist [[Eugene Newman Parker]],<ref name=\"NYT-20180810kc\">{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe Is Named for Him. 60 Years Ago, No One Believed His Ideas About the Sun. Eugene N. Parker predicted the existence of solar wind in 1958. The NASA spacecraft is the first named for a living person.\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/science/eugene-parker-solar-wind-nasa-probe.html|date=August 10, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/nasa-sun-mission-parker-solar-probe|title=Nasa's mission to Sun renamed after astrophysicist behind solar wind theory|last=Burgess|first=Matt|journal=Wired|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> coiner of the term \"[[solar wind]]\". The solar probe cost NASA US$1.5 billion.<ref>[https://www.space.com/41424-parker-solar-probe-sun-science.html How NASA's New Solar Probe Will 'Touch' the Sun on Historic Mission]. Meghan Bartels, Space.com. August 9, 2018.</ref><ref>[http://www.satnews.com/story.php?number=258258659&menu=2 Successful Launch of NASA's Parker Solar Probe.] ''SatNews Daily''. August 12, 2018.</ref> The launch rocket bore a dedication in memory of APL engineer Andrew A. Dantzler who had worked on the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Parker Solar Probe Begins Mission on Rocket Dedicated to APL's Andy Dantzler|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=102|publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |date=September 26, 2018|access-date=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Spacecraft ==\n[[File:Thermal testing of the solar array cooling system for the Parker Solar Probe.jpg|thumb|left|The thermal testing of the spacecraft.]]\n\nThe ''Parker Solar Probe'' is the first spacecraft to fly into the low solar corona. It will assess the structure and dynamics of the Sun's coronal plasma and magnetic field, the energy flow that heats the solar corona and impels the solar wind, and the mechanisms that accelerate energetic particles.\n\nThe spacecraft's systems are protected from the extreme heat and radiation near the [[Sun]] by a solar shield. Incident solar radiation at perihelion is approximately {{val|{{#expr:475*1.361 round -1}}|u=kW|up=m2}}, or 475 times the [[solar constant|intensity at Earth orbit]].{{r|extreme|Fox 2016|p2=31}} The solar shield is hexagonal, mounted on the Sun-facing side of the spacecraft, {{cvt|2.3|m|ft}} in diameter,{{r|jhuapl}} {{cvt|11.4|cm}} thick, and is made of [[reinforced carbon\u2013carbon]] composite, which is designed to withstand temperatures outside the spacecraft of about {{cvt|2500|F|C|order=flip}}.<ref name=extreme />\n\n[[File:Parker Solar Probe.webm|thumb|right|The NASA's ''Parker Solar Probe'' during extensive environmental testing.]]\nA white reflective [[alumina]] surface layer minimizes absorption. The spacecraft systems and [[scientific instruments]] are located in the central portion of the shield's shadow, where direct radiation from the Sun is fully blocked. If the shield were not between the spacecraft and the Sun, the probe would be damaged and become inoperative within tens of seconds. As radio communication with Earth will take about eight minutes in each direction, the ''Parker Solar Probe'' will have to act autonomously and rapidly to protect itself. This will be done using four light sensors to detect the first traces of direct [[sunlight]] coming from the shield limits and engaging movements from [[reaction wheels]] to reposition the spacecraft within the shadow again. According to project scientist Nicky Fox, the team describe it as \"the most autonomous spacecraft that has ever flown\".{{r|bbc22jl18}}\n\nThe primary power for the mission is a dual system of [[Solar panels on spacecraft|solar panels]] ([[Photovoltaic system|photovoltaic arrays]]). A primary photovoltaic array, used for the portion of the mission outside {{Val|0.25|u=au}}, is retracted behind the shadow shield during the close approach to the Sun, and a much smaller secondary array powers the spacecraft through closest approach. This secondary array uses pumped-fluid cooling to maintain [[operating temperature]] of the solar panels and instrumentation.<ref>{{cite conference |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20090004577.pdf|title=Solar Power System Design for the Solar Probe+ Mission|conference=6th International Energy Conversion Engineering Conference |location=Cleveland, Ohio.|first1=Geoffrey A.|last1=Landis|first2=Paul C.|last2=Schmitz|first3=James|last3=Kinnison|first4=Martin|last4=Fraeman|first5=Lew|last5=Roufberg|first6=Steve|last6=Vernon |first7=Melissa |last7=Wirzburger|display-authors=1|date=July 28\u201330, 2008|id=AIAA 2008-5712}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.techexplorist.com/traveling-sun-parker-solar-probe-melt/15586/ |title=Traveling to the Sun: Why won't Parker Solar Probe melt?|first=Pranjal|last=Mehar|website=Tech Explorist|date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Trajectory ==\n[[File:Animation of Parker Solar Probe trajectory.gif|thumb|right|An animation of ''Parker Solar Probe''{{'s}} trajectory from August 7, 2018 to August 29, 2025:<br/>{{legend2|magenta|''Parker Solar Probe''}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|Yellow|[[Sun]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|Lime|[[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|Cyan|[[Venus]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|RoyalBlue|[[Earth]]}}<br/>For more detailed animation, see [[:File:Animation of Parker Solar Probe trajectory.webm|this video.]]]]\n\nThe ''Parker Solar Probe'' mission design uses repeated [[gravity assist]]s at Venus to incrementally decrease its orbital [[perihelion]] to achieve a final altitude (above the surface) of approximately 8.5 solar radii, or about {{cvt|6|e6km|e6mi+au}}.<ref name=jhuapl>{{cite web|title=Solar Probe Plus: A NASA Mission to Touch the Sun|url=http://solarprobe.jhuapl.edu/|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|date=September 4, 2010|accessdate=September 30, 2010}}</ref> The spacecraft trajectory will include seven Venus flybys over nearly seven years to gradually shrink its elliptical orbit around the Sun, for a total of 24 orbits.{{r|extreme}} The near Sun radiation environment is predicted to cause spacecraft charging effects, radiation damage in materials and electronics, and communication interruptions, so the orbit will be highly elliptical with short times spent near the Sun.{{r|Fox 2016}}\n\nThe trajectory requires high launch energy, so the probe was launched on a [[Delta IV Heavy]] class [[launch vehicle]] and an upper stage based on the [[STAR-48|STAR 48BV]] solid rocket motor.{{r|Fox 2016}} Interplanetary [[gravity assist]]s will provide further deceleration relative to its [[heliocentric orbit]], which will result in a heliocentric speed record at [[perihelion]].{{r|Delta 4}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Scharf|first1=Caleb A.|title=The Fastest Spacecraft Ever?|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/life-unbounded/the-fastest-spacecraft-ever/|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en}}</ref> As the probe passes around the [[Sun]], it will achieve a velocity of up to {{cvt|200|km/s}}, which will temporarily make it the fastest human-made object, almost three times as fast as the previous record holder, [[Helios (spacecraft)#Helios-B|Helios-2]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aerospaceweb.org/question/performance/q0023.shtml|title=Aircraft Speed Records|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2014 |website=Aerospaceweb.org|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/66135-fastest-spacecraft-speed|title=Fastest spacecraft speed|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2015|website=guinnessworldrecords.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219024804/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/66135-fastest-spacecraft-speed |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Parker Solar Probe \u2013 Check123, Video Encyclopedia|url=https://www.check123.com/videos/13450-parker-solar-probe|language=en|accessdate=June 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810211059/https://www.check123.com/videos/13450-parker-solar-probe|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Like every object in an orbit, due to gravity the spacecraft will accelerate as it nears perihelion, then slow down again afterward until it reaches its [[aphelion]].\n\n==Mission==\n[[File:Parker Solar Probe Launch (NHQ201808120013).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Launch of ''Parker Solar Probe'' in 2018.]]\n[[File:Magnificent CME Erupts on the Sun - August 31.jpg|thumb|The overall goal is to increase understanding of Earth's star, the Sun{{mdash}} an astronomical body of immense impact on the Earth and the Solar System due to its release of light and solar wind, in addition to its large gravity. The spacecraft must contend with these forces as it approaches closer to the Sun than any probe before it.]]\nWithin each orbit of the Parker Solar Probe around the Sun, the portion within 0.25 AU will be the Science Phase, in which the probe will be actively and autonomously making observations. Communication with the probe will be largely cut off in that phase.<ref name=\"mission design\">{{cite conference|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/301998540|title=Solar Probe Plus Mission Design Overview and Mission Profile|last=Guo|first=Yanping|last2=Ozimek|first2=Martin|last3=Mcadams|first3=James|last4=Shyong|first4=Wen-Jong|date=May 2014|conference=International Symposium on Space Flight Dynamics, at Laurel, MD|website=ResearchGate}}</ref>{{rp|4}} Science phases will run for a few days both before and after each perihelion. They will last 11.6 days for the earliest perihelion, and drop to 9.6 days for the final, closest perihelion.<ref name=\"mission design\"/>{{rp|8}}\n\nMuch of the rest of each orbit will be devoted to transmitting data from the science phase. But during this part of each orbit, there will still be periods when communication is not possible. First, the heat shield of the probe must be pointed towards the Sun; there will be times when that will put the heat shield between the antenna and Earth. Second, even when the probe is not particularly near the Sun, when the angle between the probe and the Sun (as seen from Earth) is too small, the Sun's radiation will overwhelm the communication link.<ref name=\"mission design\"/>{{rp|11\u201314}}\n\n== Science goals ==\n[[File:Sun's Apparent Size as Seen From Earth vs From Solar Probe Plus's orbit.png|thumb|An apparent size of the Sun as seen from ''Parker Solar Probe'' at perihelion compared to its apparent size seen from Earth.]]\nThe goals of the mission are:<ref name=\"Fox 2016\">{{Cite journal|last=Fox|first=N.J.|last2=Velli|first2=M.C.|last3=Bale|first3=S.D.|last4=Decker|first4=R.|last5=Driesman|first5=A.|last6=Howard|first6=R.A. |last7=Kasper|first7=J.C.|last8=Kinnison|first8=J.|last9=Kusterer|first9=M.|first10=D.|last10=Lario|first11=M.K.|last11=Lockwood|first12=D.J.|last12=McComas|first13=N.E.|last13=Raouafi|first14=A.|last14=Szabo|date=November 11, 2015|title=The Solar Probe Plus Mission: Humanity's First Visit to Our Star|journal=Space Science Reviews|language=en|volume=204|issue=1\u20134|pages=7\u201348|doi=10.1007/s11214-015-0211-6 |issn=0038-6308|bibcode=2016SSRv..204....7F|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* Trace the flow of energy that heats the [[solar corona|corona]] and accelerates the [[solar wind]]\n* Determine the structure and dynamics of the [[Sun#Magnetic field|magnetic fields]] at the sources of solar wind\n* Determine what mechanisms accelerate and transport energetic particles\n\n===Investigations===\n[[File:Parker Solar Probe preparation of the Energetic Particle Instrument-Low Energy (EPI-Lo).jpg|thumb|The EPI-Lo instrument for [[Integrated Science Investigation of the Sun|IS\u2609IS]] is prepared.]]\nTo achieve these goals, the mission will perform five major experiments or investigations:<ref name=\"Fox 2016\"/>\n* Electromagnetic Fields Investigation ('''[[FIELDS]]'''){{snd}}This investigation will make direct measurements of [[Electric field|electric]] and [[magnetic field]]s, radio waves, [[Poynting vector|Poynting flux]], absolute [[plasma (physics)|plasma]] density, and [[electron temperature]]. It consists of two [[Magnetometer#Fluxgate magnetometer|flux-gate magnetometers]], a search-coil magnetometer, and 5 plasma voltage sensors. The Principal investigator is Stuart Bale, at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n* Integrated Science Investigation of the Sun ('''[[IS\u2609IS]]'''){{snd}}This investigation will measure  energetic electrons, protons and heavy ions. The instrument suite comprises two independent Energetic Particle Instruments, the EPI-Hi and EPI-Lo studying higher and lower energy particles <ref>{{cite journal|last1=McComas|first1=D.J.|last2=Alexander|first2=N.|last3=Angold|first3=N.|last4=Bale|first4=S. |last5=Beebe|first5=C.|last6=Birdwell|first6=B.|last7=Boyle|first7=M.|last8=Burgum|first8=J. M.|last9=Burnham |first9=J. A.|last10=Christian|first10=E. R.|last11=Cook|first11=W. R.|last12=Cooper|first12=S. A.|last13=Cummings|first13=A. C.|last14=Davis|first14=A. J.|last15=Desai|first15=S. I.|last16=Dickinson|first16=J.|last17=Dirks|first17=G|last18=Do|first18=D. H.|last19=Fox|first19=N.|last20=Giacalone |first20=J.|last21=Gold|first21=R. E.|last22=Gurnee|first22=R. S.|last23=Hayes|first23=J. R.|last24=Hill|first24=M. E.|last25=Kasper|first25=J. C.|last26=Kecman|first26=B.|last27=Klemic |first27=J. |last28=Krimigis|first28=S. M.|last29=Labrador|first29=A. W.|last30=Layman|first30=R. S.|last31=Leske|first31=R. A.|last32=Livi|first32=S.|last33=Mathaeus|first33=W. H.|last34=McNutt Jr.|first34=R. L. |last35=Mewaldt|first35=R. A.|last36=Mitchell|first36=D. G.|last37=Nelson|first37=K.S.|last38=Parker|first38=C.|last39=Rankin|first39=J. S.|last40=Roelof|first40=E. C.|last41=Schwadron|first41=N. A. |last42=Seifert|first42=H.|last43=Shuman|first43=S.|last44=Stokes|first44=M. R.|last45=Stone|first45=E. C.|last46=Vandergriff|first46=J. D.|last47=Velli|first47=M.|last48=von Rosenvinge|first48=T. T. |last49=Weidner|first49=S. E.|last50=Wiedenbeck|first50=M. E.|last51=Wilson IV|first51=P.|date=December 2016|title=Integrated Science Investigation of the Sun (ISIS): Design of the Energetic Particle Investigation|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=204|issue=1\u20134|pages=187\u2013156|display-authors=1|doi=10.1007/s11214-014-0059-1|bibcode=2016SSRv..204..187M|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Principal investigator is David McComas, at the [[Princeton University]]\n* Wide-field Imager for Solar Probe ('''[[WISPR]]'''){{snd}}These optical telescopes will acquire  images of the [[solar corona|corona]] and inner [[heliosphere]]. The Principal Investigator is Russell Howard, at the [[Naval Research Laboratory]]\n* Solar Wind Electrons Alphas and Protons ('''[[SWEAP]]'''){{snd}}This investigation will count the  electrons, protons and helium ions, and measure their properties such as velocity, density, and temperature. Its main instruments are the Solar Probe Analyzers (SPAN, two [[electrostatic analyzer]]s) and the Solar Probe Cup (SPC, a [[Faraday cup]]). The Principal Investigator is Justin Kasper at the [[University of Michigan]] and the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]]\n* Heliospheric Origins with Solar Probe Plus ('''HeliOSPP'''){{snd}}A theory and modeling investigation to maximize the scientific return from the mission. The Principal Investigator is Marco Velli at [[UCLA]] and the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] (JPL)\n\n== Timeline ==\nAfter the first Venus [[Planetary flyby|flyby]], the probe will be in an elliptical orbit with a period of 150 days (two-thirds the period of Venus), making three orbits while Venus makes two. On the second flyby, the period shortens to 130 days. After less than two orbits (only 198 days later) it encounters Venus a third time at a point earlier in the orbit of Venus. This encounter shortens its period to half of that of Venus, or about 112.5 days. After two orbits it meets Venus a fourth time at about the same place, shortening its period to about 102 days. After 237 days it meets Venus for the fifth time and its period is shortened to about 96 days, three-sevenths that of Venus. It then makes seven orbits while Venus makes three. The sixth encounter, almost two years after the fifth, brings its period down to 92 days, two-fifths that of Venus. After five more orbits (two orbits of Venus) it meets Venus for the seventh and last time, decreasing its period to 88 or 89 days and allowing it to approach closer to the Sun.<ref name=the_mission>See data and figure at {{cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/The-Mission/index.php#Journey-to-the-Sun |title=Solar Probe Plus: The Mission |date=2017 |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image |Velocity of Parker Solar Probe wide.svg |900px |The speed of the probe and distance from the Sun, from launch until 2026. Events: {{color|red|\u2460}}\u2013{{color|red|\u3254}}: Perihelion; {{color|lightgreen|<big>\u278a</big>}}\u2013{{color|lightgreen|<big>\u2790</big>}}: Venus flyby |center |alt=}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Scheduled events{{r|the_mission}}{{r|Fox 2016|p=31}}<ref>{{cite web |title=HORIZONS System |publisher=Jet Propulsion Laboratory, NASA |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/?horizons}} [https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/horizons_batch.cgi?batch=1&COMMAND='-96'&MAKE_EPHEM='YES'&TABLE_TYPE='VECTORS'&START_TIME='2018-Aug-12%2008:17'&STOP_TIME='2025-Aug-31%2009:18'&STEP_SIZE='1%20h'&CSV_FORMAT='YES'&CENTER='500@10'&REF_PLANE='ECLIPTIC'&REF_SYSTEM='J2000'&OUT_UNITS='AU-D'&VEC_TABLE='2'&OBJ_DATA='YES' Data file]</ref>\n! rowspan=2 | Year !! rowspan=2 | Date !! rowspan=2 | Event !! Distance<br/>from Sun (Gm){{ref|distance|a}} !! Speed <br/>(km/s) !! Orbital period<br/>(days) !! rowspan=2 | Notes\n|-\n! ''Flyby altitude<br/>over Venus''{{ref|venus|b}} !! ''Leg of<br/> Parker's orbit''{{ref|leg|c}} !! ''Inside/Outside<br/> orbit of Venus''{{ref|inside/outside|d}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2018\n| August 12<br/>07:31 UTC || bgcolor=PaleGreen    | Launch         || 151.6 || \u2013 || 174{{ref|1storbit|e}} ||\n|-\n| ''October 3<br/>08:44 UTC'' || bgcolor=PowderBlue   | ''Venus flyby #1'' || ''2548 km''{{ref|VenAlt|f}} || ''Inbound'' || ''Inside'' || ''Flybys 1 and 2 occur at the<br/>same point in Venus's orbit''\n|-\n| November 6<br/>03:27 UTC || bgcolor=Ivory        | Perihelion  #1 || {{cvt|35.66|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}}{{Ref|compare|g}} || 95 || 150 || Solar encounter phase<br/>October 31 \u2013 November 11<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=113|title=Parker Solar Probe Reports First Telemetry, Acquisition of Science Data Since Perihelion|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=November 20, 2018|website=Parker Solar Probe News Center|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2019\n| April 4<br/>22:40 UTC || bgcolor=Ivory        | Perihelion  #2 || {{cvt|35.66|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 95 || 150 || Solar encounter phase<br/>March 30 \u2013 April 10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sci-news.com/space/parker-solar-probe-second-perihelion-07067.html|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe Makes Second Close Approach to Sun|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=April 18, 2019|website=Sci-News|access-date=May 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 1<br/>17:50 UTC<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/parker-solar-probe-third-sun-flyby.html|title=NASA's Daring Solar Probe Is Skimming Past the Sun Today!|author=Meghan Bartles|date=September 1, 2019|website=Space.com|access-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref> || bgcolor=Ivory        | Perihelion  #3 || {{cvt|35.66|solar radius|Gm|1|disp=number}} || 95 || 150 || Solar encounter phase<br/>August 16 \u2013 September 20 {{Ref|obsextend|h}}\n|-\n| ''December 26''<br>''18:14 UTC''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=113|title=Parker Solar Probe Heads Toward Second Venus Flyby|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=November 20, 2018|website=Parker Solar Probe News Center|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=December 23, 2019}} Gives the time as \"1:14 p.m. EST\" and the distance of the flyby as \"within 1870 miles.\"</ref> || bgcolor=